            <h4 class="kicker">L.A. Mayor's Race</h4>
            <h1>Exit polls shows Garcetti to be all things to -- almost -- all people</h1>

            <div id="content-article-metadata">
                <p><span class="credits"><a href="http://www.scpr.org/about/people/staff/oscar-garza" target="_blank">Oscar Garza</a> &amp; <a href="http://www.scpr.org/about/people/staff/chris-keller" target="_blank">Chris Keller</a></span> | <span class="pubdate">Updated May 22, 2013</span></p>
            </div>

            <div id="content-article-text">
                <p>Tuesday night, just after the polls closed, Fernando Guerra disclosed the initial results of an election day <a href="http://studyla.org/preliminary-results/" target="blank">exit poll</a>, which predicted a victory by Eric Garcetti over Wendy Greuel by 54 percent to 46 percent.</p>
                <p>Guerra, who directs <a href="http://studyla.org/" target="blank">Loyola Marymount University's Center for the Study of Los Angeles</a>, was spot on. His numbers exactly matched the final count delivered by the L.A. City Clerk's office at 3:15 Wednesday morning.</p>
                <p>On Wednesday afternoon, the LMU center issued the details of the exit poll, and the results display just how much Garcetti dominated the race.</p>
                <p>The exit poll’s highlights include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Garcetti won in every age group — 18-29, 30-44, 45-64 and 65+ — with at least 55 percent of the vote.</li>
                    <li>Greuel won the African-American vote by a whopping 69-31 percent.</li>
                    <li>He captured votes from Democrats (53-47) and Republicans as well (61-39).</li>
                    <li>Garcetti dominated with male voters (60-40 percent).</li>
                    <li>Garcetti won the Catholic, Protestant and Jewish votes with at least 52 percent.</li>
                    <li>Greuel won among households with a resident who belongs to a public union, but her margin was .8 percent — actually a statistical tie with Garcetti.</li>
                    <li>In households outside the San Fernando Valley, Garcetti won 58 percent of the vote.</li>
                    <li>Garcetti won in every income category — with his margin increasing along with household income levels.</li>
                </ul>
